{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17487248","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17487248"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:02:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:02:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"291"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"291","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/291"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.45,0.17,0.17,0.05,0.17]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"291"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"47334"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"291","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/291"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"291"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"32053"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"311"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12554"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12555"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"47334","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/47334"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a three-day history of worsening upper abdominal pain, associated with nausea and vomiting. These symptoms have been present on an intermittent basis over the last six months and tends to be worse after meals. She feels thirsty and has lost two kilograms. She denies any fevers nor change in her bowels. She reports mild dysuria, however this is long-standing. She has a medical history of type 1 diabetes. Her medications include regular insulin, with which she is compliant. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 100/min, blood pressure 110/70mmHg, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C . Her abdomen is soft to palpation. Her blood glucose level on presentation is 10.0 mmol/L (3.2-5.5) and blood ketones 0.6 mmol/L (\u0026lt;1).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Gastroparesis","Acute pancreatitis","Diabetic ketoacidosis","Gastro-oesophageal reflux disease","Cholecystitis"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe symptoms described are suggestive of progressively worsening delayed gastric emptying ie, gastroparesis. It presents initially as nausea, vomiting, early satiety, upper abdominal pain, and bloating. A range of factors are believed to contribute to diabetic \u003Cstrong\u003Egastroparesis\u003C/strong\u003E, including autonomic neuropathy and marked hyperglycaemia. It often occurs in patients that have longstanding diabetes. The delayed gastric emptying can also increase risk of weight loss and poor glycaemic control.\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiabetic ketoacidosis \u003C/strong\u003Eis also associated with nausea, vomiting and abdominal pain, along with hyperglycaemia and its signs of polydipsia and weight loss. By definition, diabetic ketoacidosis refers to hyperglycaemia (blood glucose \u0026gt;11 mol/L), ketonaemia (blood ketones \u0026gt;3 mmol/L) and acidosis (venous pH \u0026lt;7.3 or bicarbonate \u0026lt;15 mmol/L). The patient\u2019s blood ketone levels are not consistent with this diagnosis. It would also be expected to evolve more acutely.\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAcute abdominal problems such as \u003Cstrong\u003Epancreatitis\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Echolecystitis\u003C/strong\u003E can also present with nausea, vomiting and upper abdominal pain, that may radiate to the back. Pancreatitis does not behave on an intermittent basis - such as described by this patient. If her current illness was explained by cholecystitis, the three day history would mean that she would have florid inflammation of the gallbladder by the time of presentation, and there would be right upper tenderness. The absence of any abdominal signs makes these two diagnoses unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPatients with \u003Cstrong\u003Egastro-oesophageal reflux disease\u003C/strong\u003E can have symptoms of nausea and vomiting, but in the absence of heartburn, this is an unlikely cause of this patient\u0027s current problem.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Gastroparesis should always be considered in a patient with diabetes who presents with post-prandial upper gastrointestinal symptoms."],"references":["Atkinson M, McGill D, Dassau E, Laffel L. Williams Textbook of Endocrinology. 14th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020.","Ma J, Rayner C, Jones K, Horowitz M. Diabetic Gastroparesis. Drugs. 2009;69(8):971\u201386. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/19496627/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"32053"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"291"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"32053","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/32053"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-06-20T19:52:14+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-06-20T19:52:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"291"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"47334"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"}